Banks want to solve the crisis
The Bank of the American Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks British, Swiss and Canadian decided to fight together against the crisis of the market of finances.
In the marking monetary will meet more than one hundred billion dollars through Licitaciónes.
In these tenders banks auctioned interest rates by which they can lend.
For example, the American EDF sent to bid 40 billion dollars, and then other 24 billion will facilitate the central banks of Europe and Swiss.
After the attacks of 11 September, this is the first time that central banks of different States agree on this process coordinated to protect and reduce the impact of the crisis of finance.
"This step must solve the biggest economic problem, that is, the Contínuo growth of the lack of free capital that banks could provide" wrote in his report to clients, Bernard Baumohl of the consultant economic outlook group.
"This coordinated action by the central banks probably fell recession in the United States of 65% to 50%" added Baumohl in his report.
The banks have already spent 60 billion dollars in unpaid appropriations, especially in the United States.
Economists still expect billions in losses.
"The central banks must have really fear of what awaits them even when we decided to take this step," said the chief economist of ABN, Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really evil," he added.
They fear that the central banks have the same problems of access to loans and that it will have to pay more for their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the American economy into recession with different impacts on the growth of the Economóa world.
The central banks so decided, after that were not reduce the so-called tariff Libor, tariff London used for the loan of money in the market.
This means that the banks feared constantly paid money even when the central banks of the US, Canada and Britain during the autumn reduced its interest rates several times.
"It will have the same effect as a further fall in interest rates" told the Reuters news agency, Greg Salvaggio of the company Tempus consulting.
Some economists is not that the step taken by the central banks contribute to light the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem is that the fall of the property market in the US.
