New fears about the gas between Russia and Ukraine
The dispute increased the price of gas between Ukraine and Russia, increases the risk of affecting the export of fuel to Western Europe by Russia.
Most of the gas exported by Russia to the European Union (EU) is sent via Ukraine, so each between the two nations is a source of attention.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow is increasing the price of gas, Russia will have to pay higher transit charges.
A dispute earlier last year reduced supplies to the EU Member States.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow wine with the Ukrainian Government and the Russian State, owner gas monopoly, Gazprom, trying to agree on the amount of money to be paid Ukraine for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom stated that will be more to Ukraine, because it is committed to pay 50% extra in 2008 with gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that may be that Ukraine pay 40% more for imports of Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important journeys for gas during the talks," said the Finance Minister Ukrainian Anatoly Kinakh to Reuters news agency.
"The changes in gas prices should not be linked to our arguments on the levels of the transit charges [] to Western Europe via Ukraine."
The last major dispute over gas between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut off supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a decline in exports to Western Europe, which rose rapidly prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the supply of the EU.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it is not yet fully developed.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own supply gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet nations of Central Asia.
