NHS waiting to carry out the screening of employment to the candidates, to ensure that they meet with qualifications, experience and permission to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the College of health of Scotland uses "disclosure Scotland" to carry out checks of criminal records, the Agency has no jurisdiction in order to obtain this information outside the United Kingdom.
The report of the auditor general recommends, among other things, that the Board should have the guide of the criminal Bureau, which helps employers with controls criminal in many countries outside the United Kingdom.
"Although we find some of the personal records with evidence of these controls, this is not a routine review," says the report.
Black declared that the Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with their own employment policies, but points out that: "our report highlights the areas that can be improved to ensure that the necessary information is available in the number of foreign staff of the NHS."
The President of the Bma Scotland, Dr Peter Terry said that it was "very unlikely" that the screening of Pre-empleo can identify potential employees NHS that they could commit terrorist acts in the future.
"The report suggests that the screening of Pre-empleo operate NHS in Scotland but it is not clear what the added value of the recommendations made", explained.
The authorities of health Scottish declare that currently have 1.161 foreigners, most of them doctors and nurses
But the auditor general warned that the number may be higher, partly because together have problems in identifying what the employees who have residence permits indefinite.
The research also found that the verification procedures established by the authorities in NHS Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being complied with widely.
This includes passport controls, work permit and check-up of qualifications.
The Scottish Executive is currently reviewing the policy and guide Pre-empleo of foreigners in the NHS.
The Secretary of health, Nicola sturgeon, states: "he had a great interest that this work should take place following the terrorist attack of Glasgow airport.
He went on to say that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the board of health, could consider the recommendations of the reports and that this will be reflected in the updating of directories of control of Pre-empleo for all working groups - including foreigners - what they had planned to publish next month.
