Climate of Venus can give an idea of the future of the earth
Venus may have been once an appropriate place for life, scientists said yesterday.
The data of a European space ship in orbit showed the planet more like a twin of the land of what had been noticed previously.
Venus is the planet closest to the earth.
The two planets have similar size and occupy orbits similar, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to those that made the earth a habitable planet, scientists now believe.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and the greenhouse effect, the erosion by air solar radiation and solar rotation slower Venus sent a very different kind of development.
Today the planet has no water, the temperature of the surface is enough to melt lead and it is being eroded by the storms of rays.
The results of the European Space Agency for Venus, who has studied the planet for one year, provides a picture of how the earth could develop changes catastrophic because of the climate.
Professor Fred Taylor, of the department of physics at Oxford University and one of the leaders of the mission Venus, declared: "It is clear why the climate in Venus is so different from the earth, when they are two planets so similar.
"Our new data make it possible to construct a scenario in which Venus began as land, possibly with a habitable environment makes millions of years."
