Sharks cards
The crisis of subprime mortgages is infecting the American market credit cards?
When there is blood in the water, it is only natural that a few fins Dorsales Naden around.
Today that the American market is in crisis, housing predators have their eyes on the market of the country of credit cards.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate that the losses in credit cards can reach 99 billion dollars if the crisis of subprime mortgages other forms of appropriations consumption.
Signs of infection already are.
There is an increase in the charges of cards as crime rate, which measures the proportion of balances that have not been cancelled or that are more than 30 days late respectively.
HSBC announced last month that has taken 1.4 million charge in its business of financing to the American consumer, partly because of the weakness of the providers of cards.
However, it is too early to panic.
Late payment and crime are at low levels.
According to's, a rating agency, the third quarter the crime rate of 3.89% was almost a percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the law American bankruptcy of people (2005) gave rise to a sharp fall in applications of bankruptcy, which in turn represent a major loss in credit cards; the number of applications (and therefore of late payment) would be growing again, or it may be that the conditions for borrowers were getting worse.
The industry also brings solid payment rates, which show how much of its debts paid by consumers every month.
And confidence in credit cards and values backed by assets is quite strong, despite the paralysis in other areas financial.
Dennis Moroney of Towergroup, a signature research, predicts that the volume of emissions by the year 2007 will be close to 25% higher than last year.
Direct channels of infection of the crisis between subprime mortgages and the market for credit cards certainly exists: consumers like to pay debts to credit cards now that credit institutions are ending.
But the issuer of the credit card look more the flow of liquidity asset values, so that prices fall in Accionan not necessarily a change in the capacity worthy of borrowers.
They can even work to outflank issuers.
The incentives so that consumers will continue to pay off the mortgage decreasing if the properties are worth less than the value of the loan; and as a result, the payment of the debt of the card up on the list of priorities.
Card issuers can also respond rapidly and flexibly to the difficult conditions that the mortgage lenders changing interest rates or altering balances creditors.
This in theory should reduce the risk of a Retasación rapid asset.
"We are not going to wake up one day and re-evaluate all loans," says Gary Perlin, head of finance capital one.
If a sudden infection of the subprime credit cards on the market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
If prices of homes are lower and a credit crunch driving America to the recession, the industry undoubtedly faces a future stronger.
We must continue to monitor these fins Dorsales.
